review_blob: Delicious. Well balanced combination of hops with malt. Very strong. No off flavors, only deliciousness
I thought this had a great aroma. Citrus and banana bread. Tasted bready and VERY alcoholic. Silky thick palate.
Yum! Cloudy gold with plenty of carbonation and a really thick head. Very yummy fruit flavors. Aroma of wet hay and spices. Excellent texture. Great beer, and a good representation of the style

Served at brewery. Yeasty nutty aroma. Chocolate notes light malt. Pretty yummy. Strength of the alcohol content comes through in the taste. Nice smooth not to thick not to thin consistancy. Very light finish

This is a good imperial IPA. I dont say great simply because there is no feature that is particularly outstanding for this beer in respect to other good IPAs. 

Bottle poured in tulip. orange-amber with a rapidly disappearing head. Not particularly aromatic. Typical Imperial IPA scent and taste, nothing particular to add. Nice smooth thick palate.

On tap at a bowling alley. This was a tastey brew. not much on the nose or to look at. A little more head than I see with some pilsners. However this beer does have that classic pilsner taste (think Urquel) with some strong hop and citrus flavors to give it some pizzaz. Palate has some good thickness to it. crisp finish. 

overall enjoyable casual beer. perfect for bowling

bottle poured in tulip.
Big beautiful brown head with lots of retention. this beer is a deep dark BLACK. Aroma of dark malts. Fabulous taste of dark chocolate coffee and toasted nuts. Smooth thick palate with a little bite. Yummy sweet coffee aftertaste

Pretty bland and sub-par beer. Nothing about it was outright offensive, but it was pretty darn boring. I handed this one to a friend and got a different beer about a third of the way in. 

Aroma plain wheat, bland beer flavor, thick and lightly carbonated palate.

Good double IPA at a reasonable price. I see myself coming back to this one. very unique hop aroma too.

Bottle poured in tulip glass. pretty amber brown with creamy white head. Strong hop scent that reminds me of weed. Also strong caramelly malts on the nose as well. Taste is bittersweet, hop and malts definitely shine through. Thick and heavy palate. I dig Ralph Steadman art too.
beer_name: Flying Dog Double Dog Double Pale Ale

review_blob: Corked bottle poured in tulip glass. Enjoyable, and very affordable. While its not the most distinctive dubbel ever, it is very solid by lacking in shortcomings. Dark brown with thick beige head. dark malts, desert spices, and a thick bready palate. Yum

Bottle poured in tulip glass. Dark brown with a frothy head. Aroma of banana, malts, and dark fruits. lively carbonation and a full body. Taste of dark fruits and bread. This was a good Christmas brew.

I had this a while back but I still have my notes from when I drank it. Overall I remember enjoying this beer. It poured a pretty amber with a minimal creamy head. Aroma strongly dominated by the alcohol content but apples and figs shine through as well. plenty of cabonation though I thought it was low for a Belgian strong. Malts and fruity sweetness in the taste. This is a fun beer with a fruity flavor and high alcohol content which is perfect for a cold winter day

This is an enjoyable beer, also one of my favorite for the pilsner style. Shiny clear and golden appearance in accordance with the style. Classic pils aroma with a bonus kick of grassy hop. Robust taste with light malts and some hoppy bitterness. Light palate with a clean crisp finish.

This was a pretty mediocre belgian white. It wasnt bad in any way, but it just didnt excite me very much at all. I would sooner by a blue moon. Looked pretty good, cloudy gold and a fluffy white head. Aroma had some complexity but wasnt particularly pleasing, light fruit, maybe banana, yeast, and a musty cabin smell. Not much in the taste, mellow sour and sweetness.

I really enjoyed this beer. Poured a dark orange tan, frothy head that lingered quite a while. Beautiful aroma of dark hops, malt, and pears before they have been sliced open. Flavor was strong in hops malt and barley. Go try one.

I havent tried a new "abbey ale" in a while and I enjoyed this one quite a bit. I am not sure why it is classified as a belgian strong, which is a pretty broad category, I would say it is most similar to the abbey dubbel. It poured a very dark brown with a red hue in the light. The head was thick and light brown. The aroma had a pungent wine/grape smell that reminded me of being in the cellar of a vineyard. I could also detect dark bready malts. The taste was of dark fruits and bread. The beer was full bodied, slick and of moderate thickness in mouthfeel

Bottle poured into tulip glass. Cloudy brownish gold with a big dense creamy head. Aroma of apples, spices and yeast. apples come through in the sweetness of the taste, a little spice in the flavor. For the palate, St. Bernardus feels a little heavier and less carbonated than some tripels I have had. On that note this is one of the better tripels I have had.

Years ago, this was my very first beer. As easy to get your hands on as Bud or Coors in Texas, this beer is much superior to its mainstream peers. Has a light body to match those other beers in drinkability but offers much more flavor.

pretty pecan amber color, the fizzy tan head disappears very quickly. aroma of light malt, hops, and caramel. Taste is as the aroma with a quick dry finish. 

I hear the word "metallic" used by other beer enthusiasts, though I got that sensation a little bit it wasnt that bad, might not have felt it if I wasnt looking for it.

Not a bad brew. I really like the nuttiness of the smell and flavor. Body and finish are a little weak.

Aroma was very roasty and very nutty, this followed through to the taste. Amber color thumb thick off-white head just how I want my amber ale to look.  I thought the palate was lacking. light body, and low carbonation. There was some crisp hop in the finish but it needs more UMPH.

This is one of the more unique Belgian strong ales I have tasted. It has the strongest fruit flavors I have experienced of any other beers in this category. While it isnt my favorite of all time, It stands out.

Bottle poured into trappist glass. Golden brown color, large white head. Aroma of citrus, and spices. Tasted very sweet and a lot like granny smith apples. lively carbonation typical of the genre. lingering spice in the finish.

not my favorite dubbel. The Prior 8 is much better in my opinion.

bottle poured into its own trappist goblet. Yellow brown in appearance. Small white quickly dissapating head. weak aroma of dough and malt. I got a strong taste of olives at first but that taste began to fade as the beer warmed up and aired out. on the flatter side with a full body and a drier finish.

This is a very drinkable and enjoyable beer. Pale yellow with a thumb thick white head. Strong citrus aroma some hay. yeasty citrus taste. maybe a tad of cough drop. Good palate with some thickness but a refreshing smoothness.

Bottle poured into tulip glass.

Aroma: Spicy with light fruits 
Appearance: golden with orange hue. tall rocky head plenty of retention and lacing. not surprising for a golden ale
Taste: Sweet. fruits came through really strong as did the spices.
Palate: Strong finish. Good carbonation

Overall really good golden ale. had more notable flavors than, say, duvel. I felt this beer succeeded in most areas but with slight shortcomings in most areas

Bottle poured into its own St. Bernardus trappist glass. 

Appearance: Brown with slightest yellow hue. visibly thick. finger thick tan head. everything  you want from a dubbel.
Aroma: not my favorite part of this beer. musty earthy smell with noticable alcohol. Also deep notes of brown sugar molassas and dark fruits.
Taste: malts and bread. very sweet
Palate: full body, creamy texture. The finish is short but I love the taste the beer leaves in your mouth. nothing lacking

Not the best dubbel I have ever had but it is up there. Selling point is the taste. although the palate is pretty darn good as well. I enjoyed the creaminess of the texture. A very enjoyable beer

Bottle poured into tulip glass. amber orange with a creamy white head that dissipated to leave lots of lacing. Aroma of pine and citrus, with some floral hints. Taste is all hops, hoppy crispness, hoppy sting. Also some sweetness. This is great Double IPA. Very refreshing

Bottle poured into tulip glass. A cloudy golden orange with a small white head. The aroma was strong on fruits, maybe apricot, also very floral with a hint of vanilla.This beer tastes delicious, fruity sweetness with an enjoyable sweet grassy hop flavor in the finish. The mouth feel of this beer is perfect with some very lively carbonation.

Bottle poured in mug. Dark amber brown with a phenomenal head. The head was very large, very creamy, and so much retention that it was like a solid object. The aroma was a musty yeasty smell with some banana. The taste was sweet, and a tad malty with a short finish. Medium body with some slickness to it. also, sometimes I had some astringent feelings in the finish that I felt was kind of metallic. In Sum, I thought the aroma wasnt too pleasing but the beer tasted pretty good and it was easy to drink although the aftertaste bothered me a little.

bottle poured in snifter glass. Dark golden brown with a small white head. Very roasty/toasty aroma and light malty taste to match. A very drinkable medium-light body and soft carbonation. not as creamy as advertised. pretty good brown ale.

This beer is awesome! The aroma is pumpkin pie and cinnamon which I thought was very enjoyable. Not much head to speak of but what blew my mind is that the head turned red on the top when I first poured it before fading into tan. The taste was definitely malt based, you had this bready taste that slowly turned into coffee as it was held and then swallowed. The palate was full bodied and silky smooth. Celebrator was certainly a fitting name because it definitely made me want to celebrate.

This was my second bottle of abt 12, however I did not take notes for the first one and so I wanted to have another before I rated it. Off the bat, the first bottle had a much stronger Aroma that captured my senses the instant the bottle was opened. Secondly the first bottle had a thick thick huge light BROWN head which I thought was awesome. 

This second bottle was poured into a trappist glass. Abt 12 is dark brown with a light tan head with tight bubbles. The aroma was spicy, earthy, malty, and fruity. I got pears cherries and figs. The taste was malty figgy and sweet. For the palate the abt 12 had a feel that reminds me of coca-cola and a finish of stingy spices.

This is a great beer. one of my favorites. Although I wish it was a little more consistent

Bottle in trappist glass. Aroma was a damp dough and honey with a hint of citrus interesting but not all too pleasing. Brownish orange in appearance with a tiny tan head. Taste was a bready honey-sweet. Thick and oily mouthfeel. Short finish with lingering citrus.

malty, bready aroma, but not that strong or pleasing. Brown appearance with a big tall, rocky dark tan head. Could taste the malt with some fruity sweetness. Lively carbonation, medium body. Overall good but not great
Out of bottle. Nice aroma. Very hoppy. Tangy.crisp finish. Lingering bitterness in aftertaste. Good ipa

Bottle poured into tulip glass. Aroma was very malty with some banana. Appearance was black with a ruddy brown hue. small creamy head. Taste was a malty toffee sweetness. A thick silky mouthfeel. The finish was mellow and round feeling. This is a good doppel bock.

bottle poured into tulip glass. aroma reminded me of duvel, but with a hint of ginger. Clear golden in color. Tasted spicy sweet. average carbonation, full body, clean finish. This was a very enjoyable beer

This beer was delightful. Spicy banana bread & toffee aroma. Additionally at times I thought I smelled something a little like soy sauce. Amber color with a dark tan head. The taste has the sweet bread and toffee that was detected in the aroma. Very yummy taste. Thick oily mouthfeel.

bottle poured in tulip glass. I think this beer deserves higher than a 91. The aroma was good, you could definitely detect the high alcohol content, but you also got this caramel apple scent. It was a cloudy dark golden orange. The head was small but creamy with condensed bubbles. This beer was very warm due to the high alcohol content ( I could feel it in my stomach) with some fruity caramel sweetness and a tad of bitterness. The carbonation was lively but lower in comparison to other belgian ales. Mouthfeel was medium thick with some oilyness to it. I really enjoyed drinking this beer, but that could be the 12% alcohol content talking, or maybe I just like fruit and caramel  and alcohol too much

This was my first sour ale and I found it exceptionally different for anything I have had before. I was a little shocked by the taste at first but either because it was warming up or because it is an aquired taste, I began to enjoy it thouroughly. The aroma is very strong and smelled of vinegar. There was little to no head and it was a dark brown that glistened red in the light. The taste was almost like a bitter sour wine.

This was a delicious beer. bottle poured in tulip glass. Orangish brown with a huge dense tan head with plenty of retention and lacing. Has a very sweet taste with a hint of pine, and a light bitterness in the finish. Full bodied with a medium thick mouthfeel. Excellent

I enjoyed this porter, it is a rich and gentle beer when compared to other dark and full bodied beers. The aroma was very malty, and it reminded me of grapes and syrup. The color was much like th bottle: a dark blackish brown. There was also not much head to speak of. Old Growler has a very rich taste, along with a very full body, and a thick creamy mouthfeel.
Draft served in weizen. Didnt much for me Mild malty aroma. sweet taste. Dry finish

Draft served in trappist glass. Yeasty aroma. Cloudy golden orange. Fluffy white head with plenty of lacing.t aste was sweet then sour then with a biter finish. I loved the texture of this beer: moderate thickness with some slickness. carbonation brings out the bitterness in the finish like trappist ales do.

draft beer served at a Texas Rangers game. Better than expected. mild aroma. hazy golden, thick white head. faint citrusy sweetness with a little bitterness in the finish. It had a pleasing smooth and creamy thickness with lively carbonation.

Bottle poured into glass mug. golden ruddy orange with little to no head. not surprising for an oktoberfest. light malty aroma. Has a hint of sweetness. Medium-light body and a dry finish. This is a very refreshing and drinkable beer.

I believe tha tis beer is underrated. Botle poured into tulip glass. Aroma was not excellent, malty, a tad spicy but not strong or super pleasing. It was a cloudy brownish orange with a large beige head with plenty of retention. light bitter taste rounded out by a dull sweetness. medium thick frothy mouthfeel, lively carbonation with a lingering bitter aftertaste

draught served in a normal glass. faint aroma. I almost had to inhale the beer through my nostrils, I enjoyed what I did smell though. It had a yeasty malty sort of scent. The color was a pretty red but there was almost no head at all. Taste was good grainy and a tad sweet with a very mellow round finish perhaps even a mellow sourness. I liked this feature of the beer a lot. which made up for some of its shortcomings

botle poured in tulip glass. delightful spicy aroma. thick frothy head with plenty of retention.Orange-amber and cloudy in appearance. subtle sweetness in taste. medium-full body. light bitter finish. This is a great beer and very pleasing to drink.

Draught beer served in weizen glass with an orange slice. Noticable citrus in the aroma and taste. very cloudy yellowish orange appearance. has some sweetness to it and a refreshing finish. This is one of the more solid mainstream beers.

The aroma was flowery and hoppy as advertised. Taste had some light sweetness. average body and a nice bitter finish that wasnt too intense. It was good, had a crafty feel, but still left something to be desired

bottle poured into tulip glass.hoppy apricot aroma which was pleasing. Head wasnt very large, On my second glass I actually poured pretty aggresively to give it a larger. A ruddy amber in appearance. For the taste is starts out pretty hoppy and developed a sort of sweet taste with an extremely bitter aftertaste. I would say that it is clean in h sense that it kept my mouth tingling. Overall I would say that this is a good beer but not a great beer. I felt like the complexities and the pleasures in the taste were somewhat diminished by the discomfort caused by the bitterness. I think the deScription on the back of the beer is put there so that people will try to ignore that discomfort so they can believe they are sophisticated.
